  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Lantern Festival Sent to a Fisherman
  author: Noh Gong-pil
  language: eng
  text: |-
    When festival returns to the village lanes,
    Nine streets throng with horses and wheels.
    The spirits of grass and tree stir awake,
    As rivers and mountains don fresh robes.

    I cherish idleness, seeking leave to depart,
    Yet eat my stipend without complaint of want.
    My path rests upon the virtue of good wine—
    No need to speak of fortune's rise and fall.
  footnotes:
    - The 'nine streets' likely refers to the bustling urban center during the Lantern Festival celebration.
    - The poem draws a contrast between the poet's official position (receiving a stipend) and his preference for leisure and wine, suggesting a tension between social duty and personal inclination.
